{
  "text": "Furthermore, semantic metrics define a coupling for classes based on textual information extracted from source code identifiers and comments [CITATION_1] . One such semantic metric, CCBC (Conceptual Coupling Between Classes) [CITATION_2] , captures a new dimension of coupling not addressed by structural or dynamic measures. Logical (or evolutionary) coupling [CITATION_3] , [CITATION_4] , [CITATION_5] utilizes information from repositories to capture the strength of relations among the artifacts (including source code) that are frequently co-changed. Such logical coupling metrics have been used for impact analysis [CITATION_6] , much like structural coupling metrics. Finally, Arisholm et al. [CITATION_7] introduced dynamic import (i.e., object calls) and export (i.e., called by) metrics to capture the coupling between classes and objects at runtime.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "206856132",
